snippet.textDisplay:
Most of these stories aren't sourced and aren't recorded in the ships logs nor others, and I've never been able to find a proper source for most of them, nor did Sam put any sources in the description.

Story 1: The Porter damaged two destroyers with her anchors while backing out of port. This incident wasn't recorded in the Porter's logs, or the logs of the two destroyers either side of her (USS Young and USS Cogswell), so it's safe to assume this didn't happen. This kind of incident has happened before in WW2, but the Porter did not record any such event.


Story 2: The Porter dropped a depth charge while escorting the Iowa and thus started a frantic u-boat search. This claim is also not supported by any ships log in the formation.


Story 3: The Porter suffered boiler failure escorting the Iowa and had to fall back. This event did actually take place and was recorded in the ships log.

Story 5 (and very commonly repeated): a drunk crew member on the Porter fired a 5in shell into a base commander's yard. This story is not backed up in the ships log, nor does it have a reliable source, and something as important as firing your main battery at a commander would probably be a well recorded incident if it had happened.

Story 6: She was sunk by an aircraft she had already shot down. This story is true, but told incorrectly. She did not sail over the plane, the plane sailed below her. She shot down a Kamikaze dive bomber, which landed in the water, went under the ship, and then exploded. Similarly to a more modern keel breaker torpedo, this explosion lifted the Porter out of the water and brought her back down again. The crew fought for hours to keep her afloat, but eventually she capsized and sank by the stern.

The USS William D Porter shot down several dozen Japanese aircraft, assisted in naval bombardment, troop transport, escort duties, and more. I don't think false stories, stories not backed up by real sources, should define her name.
